# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: streaming-algorithms
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:streaming-algorithms/count-min-sketch] In computing, the **count–min sketch** (**CM sketch**) is a probabilistic data structure that serves as a frequency table of events in a stream of data.
[src:streaming-algorithms/count-min-sketch] It uses hash functions to map events to frequencies, but unlike a hash table uses only sub-linear space, at the expense of overcounting some events due to collisions.
[src:streaming-algorithms/count-min-sketch] The count–min sketch was invented in 2003 by Graham Cormode and S.
[src:streaming-algorithms/count-min-sketch] Muthu Muthukrishnan and described by them in a 2005 paper.
[src:streaming-algorithms/count-min-sketch] Count–min sketch is an alternative to count sketch and AMS sketch and can be considered an implementation of a counting Bloom filter (Fan et al., 1998) or multistage-filter.
[src:streaming-algorithms/count-min-sketch] However, they are used differently and therefore sized differently: a count–min sketch typically has a sublinear number of cells, related to the desired approximation quality of the sketch, while a counting Bloom filter is more typically sized to match the number of elements in the set.
[src:streaming-algorithms/count-min-sketch] The goal of the basic version of the count–min sketch is to consume a stream of events, one at a time, and count the frequency of the different types of events in the stream.
[src:streaming-algorithms/count-min-sketch] At any time, the sketch can be queried for the frequency of a particular event type i from a universe of event types ${\mathcal {U}}$ , and will return an estimate of this frequency that is within a certain distance of the true frequency, with a certain probability.
[src:streaming-algorithms/count-min-sketch] The actual sketch data structure is a two-dimensional array of w columns and d rows.
[src:streaming-algorithms/count-min-sketch] The parameters w and d are fixed when the sketch is created, and determine the time and space needs and the probability of error when the sketch is queried for a frequency or inner product.
[src:streaming-algorithms/count-min-sketch] Associated with each of the d rows is a separate hash function; the hash functions must be pairwise independent.
[src:streaming-algorithms/count-min-sketch] The parameters w and d can be chosen by setting *w* = ⌈*e*/*ε*⌉ and *d* = ⌈ln 1/*δ*⌉, where the error in answering a query is within an additive factor of ε with probability 1 − *δ* (see below), and *e* is Euler's number.
[src:streaming-algorithms/count-min-sketch] When a new event of type i arrives we update as follows: for each row j of the table, apply the corresponding hash function to obtain a column index *k* = *h**j*(*i*).
[src:streaming-algorithms/count-min-sketch] Then increment the value in row j, column k by one.
[src:streaming-algorithms/count-min-sketch] The *point query* asks for the count of an event type i.
[src:streaming-algorithms/count-min-sketch] The estimated count is given by the least value in the table for i, namely ${\hat {a}}_{i}=\min _{j}\mathrm {count} [j,h_{j}(i)]$ , where $\mathrm {count}$ is the table.
[src:streaming-algorithms/count-min-sketch] Obviously, for each i, one has $a_{i}\leq {\hat {a}}_{i}$ , where $a_{i}$ is the true frequency with which i occurred in the stream.
[src:streaming-algorithms/count-min-sketch] Additionally, this estimate has the guarantee that ${\hat {a}}_{i}\leq a_{i}+\varepsilon N$ with probability $1-\delta$ , where $N=\sum _{i\in {\mathcal {U}}}a_{i}$ is the stream size, i.e. the total number of items seen by the sketch.
[src:streaming-algorithms/count-min-sketch] An *inner product query* asks for the inner product between the histograms represented by two count–min sketches, $\mathrm {count} _{a}$ and $\mathrm {count} _{b}$ .
[src:streaming-algorithms/count-min-sketch] The inner product can then be estimated as ${\widehat {a\cdot b}}=\min _{j}{\widehat {a\cdot b}}_{j}$ .
[src:streaming-algorithms/count-min-sketch] Like the count sketch, the Count–min sketch is a linear sketch.
[src:streaming-algorithms/count-min-sketch] That is, given two streams, constructing a sketch on each stream and summing the sketches yields the same result as concatenating the streams and constructing a sketch on the concatenated streams.
[src:streaming-algorithms/count-min-sketch] This makes the sketch mergeable and appropriate for use in distributed settings in addition to streaming ones.
[src:streaming-algorithms/count-min-sketch] One potential problem with the usual min estimator for count–min sketches is that they are biased estimators of the true frequency of events: they may overestimate, but never underestimate the true count in a point query.
[src:streaming-algorithms/count-min-sketch] Furthermore, while the min estimator works well when the distribution is highly skewed, other sketches such as the Count sketch based on means are more accurate when the distribution is not sufficiently skewed.
[src:streaming-algorithms/count-min-sketch] Several variations on the sketch have been proposed to reduce error and reduce or eliminate bias.
[src:streaming-algorithms/count-min-sketch] To remove bias, the `hCount*` estimator repeatedly randomly selects d random entries in the sketch and takes the minimum to obtain an unbiased estimate of the bias and subtracts it off.
[src:streaming-algorithms/count-min-sketch] A maximum likelihood estimator (MLE) was derived in Ting.
[src:streaming-algorithms/count-min-sketch] By using the MLE, the estimator is always able to match or better the min estimator and works well even if the distribution is not skewed.
[src:streaming-algorithms/count-min-sketch] This paper also showed the hCount* debiasing operation is a bootstrapping procedure that can be efficiently computed without random sampling and can be generalized to any estimator.
[src:streaming-algorithms/count-min-sketch] Since errors arise from hash collisions with unknown items from the universe, several approaches correct for the collisions when multiple elements of the universe are known or queried for simultaneously .
[src:streaming-algorithms/count-min-sketch] For each of these, a large proportion of the universe must be known to observe a significant benefit.
[src:streaming-algorithms/data-stream-management-system] A **data stream management system** (DSMS) is a computer software system to manage continuous data streams.
[src:streaming-algorithms/data-stream-management-system] It is similar to a database management system (DBMS), which is, however, designed for static data in conventional databases.
[src:streaming-algorithms/data-stream-management-system] A DBMS also offers a flexible query processing so that the information needed can be expressed using queries.
[src:streaming-algorithms/data-stream-management-system] However, in contrast to a DBMS, a DSMS executes a *continuous query* that is not only performed once, but is permanently installed.
[src:streaming-algorithms/data-stream-management-system] Therefore, the query is continuously executed until it is explicitly uninstalled.
[src:streaming-algorithms/data-stream-management-system] Since most DSMS are data-driven, a continuous query produces new results as long as new data arrive at the system.
[src:streaming-algorithms/data-stream-management-system] This basic concept is similar to complex event processing so that both technologies are partially coalescing.
[src:streaming-algorithms/data-stream-management-system] One important feature of a DSMS is the possibility to handle potentially infinite and rapidly changing data streams by offering flexible processing at the same time, although there are only limited resources such as main memory.
[src:streaming-algorithms/data-stream-management-system] The following table provides various principles of DSMS and compares them to traditional DBMS.
[src:streaming-algorithms/data-stream-management-system] One of the biggest challenges for a DSMS is to handle potentially infinite data streams using a fixed amount of memory and no random access to the data.
[src:streaming-algorithms/data-stream-management-system] There are different approaches to limit the amount of data in one pass, which can be divided into two classes.
[src:streaming-algorithms/data-stream-management-system] For the one hand, there are compression techniques that try to summarize the data and for the other hand there are window techniques that try to portion the data into (finite) parts.
[src:streaming-algorithms/data-stream-management-system] The idea behind compression techniques is to maintain only a synopsis of the data, but not all (raw) data points of the data stream.
[src:streaming-algorithms/data-stream-management-system] The algorithms range from selecting random data points called sampling to summarization using histograms, wavelets or sketching.
[src:streaming-algorithms/data-stream-management-system] One simple example of a compression is the continuous calculation of an average.
[src:streaming-algorithms/data-stream-management-system] Instead of memorizing each data point, the synopsis only holds the sum and the number of items.
[src:streaming-algorithms/data-stream-management-system] The average can be calculated by dividing the sum by the number.
[src:streaming-algorithms/data-stream-management-system] However, it should be mentioned that synopses cannot reflect the data accurately.
[src:streaming-algorithms/data-stream-management-system] Thus, a processing that is based on synopses may produce inaccurate results.
[src:streaming-algorithms/data-stream-management-system] Instead of using synopses to compress the characteristics of the whole data streams, window techniques only look on a portion of the data.
[src:streaming-algorithms/data-stream-management-system] This approach is motivated by the idea that only the most recent data are relevant.
[src:streaming-algorithms/data-stream-management-system] Therefore, a window continuously cuts out a part of the data stream, e.g. the last ten data stream elements, and only considers these elements during the processing.
[src:streaming-algorithms/data-stream-management-system] There are different kinds of such windows like sliding windows that are similar to FIFO lists or tumbling windows that cut out disjoint parts.
[src:streaming-algorithms/data-stream-management-system] Furthermore, the windows can also be differentiated into element-based windows, e.g., to consider the last ten elements, or time-based windows, e.g., to consider the last ten seconds of data.
[src:streaming-algorithms/data-stream-management-system] There are also different approaches to implementing windows.
[src:streaming-algorithms/data-stream-management-system] There are, for example, approaches that use timestamps or time intervals for system-wide windows or buffer-based windows for each single processing step.
[src:streaming-algorithms/data-stream-management-system] Sliding-window query processing is also suitable to being implemented in parallel processors by exploiting parallelism between different windows and/or within each window extent.
[src:streaming-algorithms/data-stream-management-system] Since there are a lot of prototypes, there is no standardized architecture.
[src:streaming-algorithms/data-stream-management-system] However, most DSMS are based on the query processing in DBMS by using declarative languages to express queries, which are translated into a plan of operators.
[src:streaming-algorithms/data-stream-management-system] These plans can be optimized and executed.
[src:streaming-algorithms/data-stream-management-system] A query processing often consists of the following steps.
[src:streaming-algorithms/data-stream-management-system] The formulation of queries is mostly done using declarative languages like SQL in DBMS.
[src:streaming-algorithms/data-stream-management-system] Since there are no standardized query languages to express continuous queries, there are a lot of languages and variations.
[src:streaming-algorithms/data-stream-management-system] However, most of them are based on SQL, such as the Continuous Query Language (CQL), StreamSQL and ESP.
[src:streaming-algorithms/data-stream-management-system] There are also graphical approaches where each processing step is a box and the processing flow is expressed by arrows between the boxes.
[src:streaming-algorithms/data-stream-management-system] The language strongly depends on the processing model.
[src:streaming-algorithms/data-stream-management-system] For example, if windows are used for the processing, the definition of a window has to be expressed.
[src:streaming-algorithms/data-stream-management-system] This stream continuously calculates the average value of "price" of the last 10 tuples, but only considers those tuples whose prices are greater than 100.0.
[src:streaming-algorithms/data-stream-management-system] In the next step, the declarative query is translated into a logical query plan.
[src:streaming-algorithms/data-stream-management-system] A query plan is a directed graph where the nodes are operators and the edges describe the processing flow.
[src:streaming-algorithms/data-stream-management-system] Each operator in the query plan encapsulates the semantic of a specific operation, such as filtering or aggregation.
[src:streaming-algorithms/data-stream-management-system] In DSMSs that process relational data streams, the operators are equal or similar to the operators of the Relational algebra, so that there are operators for selection, projection, join, and set operations.
[src:streaming-algorithms/data-stream-management-system] This operator concept allows the very flexible and versatile processing of a DSMS.
[src:streaming-algorithms/data-stream-management-system] The logical query plan can be optimized, which strongly depends on the streaming model.
[src:streaming-algorithms/data-stream-management-system] The basic concepts for optimizing continuous queries are equal to those from database systems.
[src:streaming-algorithms/data-stream-management-system] If there are relational data streams and the logical query plan is based on relational operators from the Relational algebra, a query optimizer can use the algebraic equivalences to optimize the plan.
[src:streaming-algorithms/data-stream-management-system] These may be, for example, to push selection operators down to the sources, because they are not so computationally intensive like join operators.
[src:streaming-algorithms/data-stream-management-system] Furthermore, there are also cost-based optimization techniques like in DBMS, where a query plan with the lowest costs is chosen from different equivalent query plans.
[src:streaming-algorithms/data-stream-management-system] One example is to choose the order of two successive join operators.
[src:streaming-algorithms/data-stream-management-system] In DBMS this decision is mostly done by certain statistics of the involved databases.
[src:streaming-algorithms/data-stream-management-system] But, since the data of a data streams is unknown in advance, there are no such statistics in a DSMS.
[src:streaming-algorithms/data-stream-management-system] However, it is possible to observe a data stream for a certain time to obtain some statistics.
[src:streaming-algorithms/data-stream-management-system] Using these statistics, the query can also be optimized later.
[src:streaming-algorithms/data-stream-management-system] So, in contrast to a DBMS, some DSMS allows to optimize the query even during runtime.
[src:streaming-algorithms/data-stream-management-system] Therefore, a DSMS needs some plan migration strategies to replace a running query plan with a new one.
[src:streaming-algorithms/data-stream-management-system] Since a logical operator is only responsible for the semantics of an operation but does not consist of any algorithms, the logical query plan must be transformed into an executable counterpart.
[src:streaming-algorithms/data-stream-management-system] The distinction between a logical and a physical operator plan allows more than one implementation for the same logical operator.
[src:streaming-algorithms/data-stream-management-system] The join, for example, is logically the same, although it can be implemented by different algorithms like a Nested loop join or a Sort-merge join.
[src:streaming-algorithms/data-stream-management-system] Notice, these algorithms also strongly depend on the used stream and processing model.
[src:streaming-algorithms/data-stream-management-system] Finally, the query is available as a physical query plan.
[src:streaming-algorithms/data-stream-management-system] Since the physical query plan consists of executable algorithms, it can be directly executed.
[src:streaming-algorithms/data-stream-management-system] For this, the physical query plan is installed into the system.
[src:streaming-algorithms/data-stream-management-system] The bottom of the graph (of the query plan) is connected to the incoming sources, which can be everything like connectors to sensors.
[src:streaming-algorithms/data-stream-management-system] The top of the graph is connected to the outgoing sinks, which may be for example a visualization.
[src:streaming-algorithms/data-stream-management-system] Since most DSMSs are data-driven, a query is executed by pushing the incoming data elements from the source through the query plan to the sink.
[src:streaming-algorithms/data-stream-management-system] Each time when a data element passes an operator, the operator performs its specific operation on the data element and forwards the result to all successive operators.
[src:streaming-algorithms/flajolet-martin-algorithm] The **Flajolet–Martin algorithm** is an algorithm for approximating the number of distinct elements in a stream with a single pass and space-consumption logarithmic in the maximal number of possible distinct elements in the stream (the count-distinct problem).
[src:streaming-algorithms/flajolet-martin-algorithm] The algorithm was introduced by Philippe Flajolet and G.
[src:streaming-algorithms/flajolet-martin-algorithm] Nigel Martin in their 1984 article "Probabilistic Counting Algorithms for Data Base Applications".
[src:streaming-algorithms/flajolet-martin-algorithm] Later it has been refined in "LogLog counting of large cardinalities" by Marianne Durand and Philippe Flajolet, and "HyperLogLog: The analysis of a near-optimal cardinality estimation algorithm" by Philippe Flajolet et al.
[src:streaming-algorithms/flajolet-martin-algorithm] In their 2010 article "An optimal algorithm for the distinct elements problem", Daniel M.
[src:streaming-algorithms/flajolet-martin-algorithm] Woodruff give an improved algorithm, which uses nearly optimal space and has optimal *O*(1) update and reporting times.
[src:streaming-algorithms/flajolet-martin-algorithm] Assume that we are given a hash function $\mathrm {hash} (x)$ that maps input x to integers in the range $[0;2^{L}-1]$ , and where the outputs are sufficiently uniformly distributed.
[src:streaming-algorithms/flajolet-martin-algorithm] Note that the set of integers from 0 to $2^{L}-1$ corresponds to the set of binary strings of length L .
[src:streaming-algorithms/flajolet-martin-algorithm] Note that with the above definition we are using 0-indexing for the positions, starting from the least significant bit.
[src:streaming-algorithms/flajolet-martin-algorithm] For example, $\rho (13)=\rho (1101_{2})=0$ , since the least significant bit is a 1 (0th position), and $\rho (8)=\rho (1000_{2})=3$ , since the least significant set bit is at the 3rd position.
[src:streaming-algorithms/flajolet-martin-algorithm] Let R denote the smallest index i such that $\mathrm {BITMAP} [i]=0$ .
[src:streaming-algorithms/flajolet-martin-algorithm] Estimate the cardinality of M as $2^{R}/\phi$ , where $\phi \approx 0.77351$ .
[src:streaming-algorithms/flajolet-martin-algorithm] The idea is that if n is the number of distinct elements in the multiset M , then $\mathrm {BITMAP} [0]$ is accessed approximately $n/2$ times, $\mathrm {BITMAP} [1]$ is accessed approximately $n/4$ times and so on.
[src:streaming-algorithms/flajolet-martin-algorithm] Consequently, if $i\gg \log _{2}n$ , then $\mathrm {BITMAP} [i]$ is almost certainly 0, and if $i\ll \log _{2}n$ , then $\mathrm {BITMAP} [i]$ is almost certainly 1.
[src:streaming-algorithms/flajolet-martin-algorithm] If $i\approx \log _{2}n$ , then $\mathrm {BITMAP} [i]$ can be expected to be either 1 or 0.
[src:streaming-algorithms/flajolet-martin-algorithm] The correction factor $\phi \approx 0.77351$ (OEIS: A244256) is found by calculations, which can be found in the original article.
[src:streaming-algorithms/flajolet-martin-algorithm] A problem with the Flajolet–Martin algorithm in the above form is that the results vary significantly.
[src:streaming-algorithms/flajolet-martin-algorithm] A common solution has been to run the algorithm multiple times with k different hash functions and combine the results from the different runs.
[src:streaming-algorithms/flajolet-martin-algorithm] One idea is to take the mean of the k results together from each hash function, obtaining a single estimate of the cardinality.
[src:streaming-algorithms/flajolet-martin-algorithm] The problem with this is that averaging is very susceptible to outliers (which are likely here).
[src:streaming-algorithms/flajolet-martin-algorithm] A different idea is to use the median, which is less prone to be influences by outliers.
[src:streaming-algorithms/flajolet-martin-algorithm] The problem with this is that the results can only take form $2^{R}/\phi$ , where R is integer.
[src:streaming-algorithms/flajolet-martin-algorithm] A common solution is to combine both the mean and the median: Create $k\cdot l$ hash functions and split them into k distinct groups (each of size l ).
[src:streaming-algorithms/flajolet-martin-algorithm] Within each group use the mean for aggregating together the l results, and finally take the median of the k group estimates as the final estimate.
[src:streaming-algorithms/flajolet-martin-algorithm] The 2007 HyperLogLog algorithm splits the multiset into subsets and estimates their cardinalities, then it uses the harmonic mean to combine them into an estimate for the original cardinality.
[src:streaming-algorithms/hyperloglog] In the original paper by Flajolet *et al.* and in related literature on the count-distinct problem, the term "cardinality" is used to mean the number of distinct elements in a data stream with repeated elements.
[src:streaming-algorithms/hyperloglog] However in the theory of multisets the term refers to the sum of multiplicities of each member of a multiset.
[src:streaming-algorithms/hyperloglog] This article chooses to use Flajolet's definition for consistency with the sources.
[src:streaming-algorithms/hyperloglog] The basis of the HyperLogLog algorithm is the observation that the cardinality of a multiset of uniformly distributed random numbers can be estimated by calculating the maximum number of leading zeros in the binary representation of each number in the set.
[src:streaming-algorithms/hyperloglog] If the maximum number of leading zeros observed is *n*, an estimate for the number of distinct elements in the set is 2*n*.
[src:streaming-algorithms/hyperloglog] In the HyperLogLog algorithm, a hash function is applied to each element in the original multiset to obtain a multiset of uniformly distributed random numbers with the same cardinality as the original multiset.
[src:streaming-algorithms/hyperloglog] The cardinality of this randomly distributed set can then be estimated using the algorithm above.
[src:streaming-algorithms/hyperloglog] The simple estimate of cardinality obtained using the algorithm above has the disadvantage of a large variance.
[src:streaming-algorithms/hyperloglog] The HyperLogLog has three main operations: **add** to add a new element to the set, **count** to obtain the cardinality of the set and **merge** to obtain the union of two sets.
[src:streaming-algorithms/hyperloglog] Some derived operations can be computed using the inclusion–exclusion principle like the **cardinality of the intersection** or the **cardinality of the difference** between two HyperLogLogs combining the merge and count operations.
[src:streaming-algorithms/hyperloglog] The data of the HyperLogLog is stored in an array M of m counters (or "registers") that are initialized to 0.
[src:streaming-algorithms/hyperloglog] The add operation consists of computing the hash of the input data v with a hash function h, getting the first b bits (where b is ${\textstyle \log _{2}(m)}$ ), and adding 1 to them to obtain the address of the register to modify (assuming 1-based indexing).
[src:streaming-algorithms/hyperloglog] With the remaining bits as w, compute ${\textstyle \rho (w)}$ which returns the position of the leftmost 1, where leftmost position is 1 (in other words: number of leading zeros plus 1).
[src:streaming-algorithms/hyperloglog] The new value of the register will be the maximum between the current value of the register and ${\textstyle \rho (w)}$ .
[src:streaming-algorithms/hyperloglog] The intuition is that n being the unknown cardinality of M, each subset ${\textstyle M_{j}}$ will have ${\textstyle n/m}$ elements.
[src:streaming-algorithms/hyperloglog] The harmonic mean of 2 to these quantities is ${\textstyle mZ}$ which should be near ${\textstyle n/m}$ .
[src:streaming-algorithms/hyperloglog] Thus, ${\textstyle m^{2}Z}$ should be n approximately.
[src:streaming-algorithms/hyperloglog] Finally, the constant ${\textstyle \alpha _{m}}$ is introduced to correct a systematic multiplicative bias present in ${\textstyle m^{2}Z}$ due to hash collisions.
[src:streaming-algorithms/hyperloglog] The HyperLogLog technique, though, is biased for small cardinalities below a threshold of ${\textstyle {\frac {5}{2}}m}$ .
[src:streaming-algorithms/hyperloglog] The original paper proposes using a different algorithm for small cardinalities known as Linear Counting.
[src:streaming-algorithms/hyperloglog] If ${\textstyle V=0}$ , use the standard HyperLogLog estimator ${\textstyle E}$ above.
[src:streaming-algorithms/hyperloglog] With the above corrections for lower and upper bounds, the error can be estimated as ${\textstyle \sigma =1.04/{\sqrt {m}}}$ .
[src:streaming-algorithms/hyperloglog] To analyze the complexity, the data streaming $(\epsilon ,\delta )$ model is used, which analyzes the space necessary to get a $1\pm \epsilon$ approximation with a fixed success probability $1-\delta$ .
[src:streaming-algorithms/hyperloglog] The relative error of HLL is $1.04/{\sqrt {m}}$ and it needs $O(\epsilon ^{-2}\log \log n+\log n)$ space, where n is the set cardinality and m is the number of registers (usually less than one byte size).
[src:streaming-algorithms/hyperloglog] The **add** operation depends on the size of the output of the hash function.
[src:streaming-algorithms/hyperloglog] As this size is fixed, we can consider the running time for the add operation to be $O(1)$ .
[src:streaming-algorithms/hyperloglog] The **count** and **merge** operations depend on the number of registers m and have a theoretical cost of $O(m)$ .
[src:streaming-algorithms/hyperloglog] In some implementations (Redis) the number of registers is fixed and the cost is considered to be $O(1)$ in the documentation.
[src:streaming-algorithms/hyperloglog] When the data arrives in a single stream, the Historic Inverse Probability or martingale estimator significantly improves the accuracy of the HLL sketch and uses 36% less memory to achieve a given error level.
[src:streaming-algorithms/hyperloglog] This estimator is provably optimal for any duplicate insensitive approximate distinct counting sketch on a single stream.
[src:streaming-algorithms/hyperloglog] The single stream scenario also leads to variants in the HLL sketch construction.
[src:streaming-algorithms/hyperloglog] HLL-TailCut+ uses 45% less memory than the original HLL sketch but at the cost of being dependent on the data insertion order and not being able to merge sketches.
[src:streaming-algorithms/misra-gries-summary] In the field of streaming algorithms, **Misra–Gries summaries** are used to solve the frequent elements problem in the data stream model.
[src:streaming-algorithms/misra-gries-summary] That is, given a long stream of input that can only be examined once (and in some arbitrary order), the Misra-Gries algorithm can be used to compute which (if any) value makes up a majority of the stream, or more generally, the set of items that constitute some fixed fraction of the stream.
[src:streaming-algorithms/misra-gries-summary] The term "summary" is due to Graham Cormode.
[src:streaming-algorithms/misra-gries-summary] The algorithm was presented by Misra and Gries alongside a different algorithm for finding frequent elements, the Misra–Gries heavy hitters algorithm.
[src:streaming-algorithms/misra-gries-summary] As for all algorithms in the data stream model, the input is a finite sequence of integers from a finite domain.
[src:streaming-algorithms/misra-gries-summary] The algorithm outputs an associative array which has values from the stream as keys, and estimates of their frequency as the corresponding values.
[src:streaming-algorithms/misra-gries-summary] It takes a parameter *k* which determines the size of the array, which impacts both the quality of the estimates and the amount of memory used.
[src:streaming-algorithms/misra-gries-summary] The Misra–Gries algorithm uses O(*k*(log(*m*)+log(*n*))) space, where *m* is the number of distinct values in the stream and *n* is the length of the stream.
[src:streaming-algorithms/misra-gries-summary] The factor *k* accounts for the number of entries that are kept in the associative array *A*.
[src:streaming-algorithms/misra-gries-summary] Each entry consists of a value *i* and an associated counter *c*.
[src:streaming-algorithms/misra-gries-summary] The counter *c* can, in principle, take any value in {0,...,*n*}, which requires ⌈log(*n*+1)⌉ bits to store.
[src:streaming-algorithms/misra-gries-summary] Assuming that the values *i* are integers in {0,...,*m*-1}, storing them requires ⌈log(*m*)⌉ bits.
[src:streaming-algorithms/misra-gries-summary] Every item which occurs more than *n*/*k* times is guaranteed to appear in the output array.
[src:streaming-algorithms/misra-gries-summary] Therefore, in a second pass over the data, the exact frequencies for the *k*−1 items can be computed to solve the frequent items problem, or in the case of *k*=2, the majority problem.
[src:streaming-algorithms/misra-gries-summary] With the same arguments as above, this second pass also takes O(*k*(log(*m*)+log(*n*))) space.
[src:streaming-algorithms/misra-gries-summary] Note that 4 is appearing 5 times in the data stream which is more than n/k=4 times and thus should appear as the output of the algorithm.
[src:streaming-algorithms/misra-gries-summary] Since k=2 and |keys(A)|=k−1=1 the algorithm can only have one key with its corresponding value.
[src:streaming-algorithms/reservoir-sampling] Suppose we see a sequence of items, one at a time.
[src:streaming-algorithms/reservoir-sampling] We want to keep 10 items in memory, and we want them to be selected at random from the sequence.
[src:streaming-algorithms/reservoir-sampling] If we know the total number of items n and can access the items arbitrarily, then the solution is easy: select 10 distinct indices i between 1 and n with equal probability, and keep the i-th elements.
[src:streaming-algorithms/reservoir-sampling] The problem is that we do not always know the exact n in advance.
[src:streaming-algorithms/reservoir-sampling] A simple and popular but slow algorithm, *Algorithm R*, was created by Jeffrey Vitter.
[src:streaming-algorithms/reservoir-sampling] Initialize an array R indexed from 1 to k , containing the first k items of the input $x_{1},...,x_{k}$ .
[src:streaming-algorithms/reservoir-sampling] For each new input $x_{i}$ , generate a random number j uniformly in $\{1,...,i\}$ .
[src:streaming-algorithms/reservoir-sampling] Return R after all inputs are processed.
[src:streaming-algorithms/reservoir-sampling] This algorithm works by induction on $i\geq k$ .
[src:streaming-algorithms/reservoir-sampling] When $i=k$ , Algorithm R returns all inputs, thus providing the basis for a proof by mathematical induction.
[src:streaming-algorithms/reservoir-sampling] Apply Algorithm R to the $(i+1)$ -th input.
[src:streaming-algorithms/reservoir-sampling] Input $x_{i+1}$ is included with probability ${\frac {k}{i+1}}$ by definition of the algorithm.
[src:streaming-algorithms/reservoir-sampling] For any other input $x_{r}\in \{x_{1},...,x_{i}\}$ , by the induction hypothesis, the probability that it is included in the reservoir just before the $(i+1)$ -th input is processed is ${\frac {k}{i}}$ .
[src:streaming-algorithms/reservoir-sampling] The probability that it is still included in the reservoir after $x_{i+1}$ is processed (in other words, that $x_{r}$ is not replaced by $x_{i+1}$ ) is ${\frac {k}{i}}\times \left(1-{\frac {1}{i+1}}\right)={\frac {k}{i+1}}$ .
[src:streaming-algorithms/reservoir-sampling] The latter follows from the assumption that the integer j is generated uniformly at random; once it becomes clear that a replacement will in fact occur, the probability that $x_{r}$ in particular is replaced by $x_{i+1}$ is ${\frac {k}{i+1}}{\frac {1}{k}}={\frac {1}{i+1}}$ .
[src:streaming-algorithms/reservoir-sampling] We have shown that the probability that a new input enters the reservoir is equal to the probability that an existing input in the reservoir is retained.
[src:streaming-algorithms/reservoir-sampling] Therefore, we conclude by the principle of mathematical induction that Algorithm R does indeed produce a uniform random sample of the inputs.
[src:streaming-algorithms/reservoir-sampling] While conceptually simple and easy to understand, this algorithm needs to generate a random number for each item of the input, including the items that are discarded.
[src:streaming-algorithms/reservoir-sampling] The algorithm's asymptotic running time is thus $O(n)$ .
[src:streaming-algorithms/reservoir-sampling] Generating this amount of randomness and the linear run time causes the algorithm to be unnecessarily slow if the input population is large.
[src:streaming-algorithms/reservoir-sampling] If we generate n random numbers $u_{1},...,u_{n}\sim U[0,1]$ independently, then the indices of the smallest k of them is a uniform sample of the k -subsets of $\{1,...,n\}$ .
[src:streaming-algorithms/reservoir-sampling] Now couple this with the stream of inputs $x_{1},...,x_{n}$ .
[src:streaming-algorithms/reservoir-sampling] Every time some $u_{i}$ is accepted, store the corresponding $x_{i}$ .
[src:streaming-algorithms/reservoir-sampling] Every time some $u_{i}$ is discarded, discard the corresponding $x_{i}$ .
[src:streaming-algorithms/reservoir-sampling] This algorithm still needs $O(n)$ random numbers, thus taking $O(n)$ time.
[src:streaming-algorithms/reservoir-sampling] Second simplification: it's unnecessary to remember the entire array of the smallest k of $u_{1},...,u_{i}$ that has been seen so far, but merely w , the largest among them.
[src:streaming-algorithms/reservoir-sampling] This algorithm computes three random numbers for each item that becomes part of the reservoir, and does not spend any time on items that do not.
[src:streaming-algorithms/reservoir-sampling] Its expected running time is thus $O(k(1+\log(n/k)))$ , which is optimal.
[src:streaming-algorithms/reservoir-sampling] At the same time, it is simple to implement efficiently and does not depend on random deviates from exotic or hard-to-compute distributions.
[src:streaming-algorithms/reservoir-sampling] If we associate with each item of the input a uniformly generated random number, the k items with the largest (or, equivalently, smallest) associated values form a simple random sample.
[src:streaming-algorithms/reservoir-sampling] A simple reservoir-sampling thus maintains the k items with the currently largest associated values in a priority queue.
[src:streaming-algorithms/reservoir-sampling] The expected running time of this algorithm is $O(n+k\log k\log(n/k))$ and it is relevant mainly because it can easily be extended to items with weights.
[src:streaming-algorithms/reservoir-sampling] The methods presented in the previous sections do not allow to obtain a priori fixed inclusion probabilities.
[src:streaming-algorithms/reservoir-sampling] Some applications require items' sampling probabilities to be according to weights associated with each item.
[src:streaming-algorithms/reservoir-sampling] For example, it might be required to sample queries in a search engine with weight as number of times they were performed so that the sample can be analyzed for overall impact on user experience.
[src:streaming-algorithms/reservoir-sampling] Let the weight of item i be $w_{i}$ , and the sum of all weights be W.
[src:streaming-algorithms/reservoir-sampling] The probability of each item to be included in the random sample is proportional to its relative weight, i.e., $w_{i}/W$ .
[src:streaming-algorithms/reservoir-sampling] It is not achievable when $k=n$ , since each item is then included with probability 1.
[src:streaming-algorithms/reservoir-sampling] This algorithm is identical to the algorithm given in Reservoir Sampling with Random Sort except for the generation of the items' keys.
[src:streaming-algorithms/reservoir-sampling] The algorithm is equivalent to assigning each item a key $r^{1/w_{i}}$ where r is the random number and then selecting the k items with the largest keys.
[src:streaming-algorithms/reservoir-sampling] Equivalently, a more numerically stable formulation of this algorithm computes the keys as $-\ln(r)/w_{i}$ and select the k items with the *smallest* keys.
[src:streaming-algorithms/reservoir-sampling] This algorithm follows the same mathematical properties that are used in A-Res, but instead of calculating the key for each item and checking whether that item should be inserted or not, it calculates an exponential jump to the next item which will be inserted.
[src:streaming-algorithms/reservoir-sampling] This avoids having to create random variates for each item, which may be expensive.
[src:streaming-algorithms/reservoir-sampling] The number of random variates required is reduced from $O(n)$ to $O(k\log(n/k))$ in expectation, where k is the reservoir size, and n is the number of items in the stream.
[src:streaming-algorithms/reservoir-sampling] Warning: the following description is wrong, see Chao's original paper and the discussion here.
[src:streaming-algorithms/reservoir-sampling] Chao uses interpretation 2: and Tillé (2006).
[src:streaming-algorithms/reservoir-sampling] For each item, its relative weight is calculated and used to randomly decide if the item will be added into the reservoir.
[src:streaming-algorithms/reservoir-sampling] If the item is selected, then one of the existing items of the reservoir is uniformly selected and replaced with the new item.
[src:streaming-algorithms/reservoir-sampling] The trick here is that, if the probabilities of all items in the reservoir are already proportional to their weights, then by selecting uniformly which item to replace, the probabilities of all items remain proportional to their weight after the replacement.
[src:streaming-algorithms/reservoir-sampling] Note that Chao doesn't specify how to sample the first *k* elements.
[src:streaming-algorithms/reservoir-sampling] He simple assumes we have some other way of picking them in proportion to their weight.
[src:streaming-algorithms/reservoir-sampling] Chao: "Assume that we have a sampling plan of fixed size with respect to *S_k* at time *A*; such that its first-order inclusion probability of *X_t* is *π(k; i)*".
[src:streaming-algorithms/reservoir-sampling] Similar to the other algorithms, it is possible to compute a random weight `j` and subtract items' probability mass values, skipping them while `j > 0`, reducing the number of random numbers that have to be generated.
[src:streaming-algorithms/reservoir-sampling] In machine learning applications, fairness is a critical consideration, especially in scenarios where data streams exhibit class imbalance.
[src:streaming-algorithms/reservoir-sampling] To address this, Nikoloutsopoulos, Titsias, and Koutsopoulos proposed the Kullback-Leibler Reservoir Sampling (KLRS) algorithm as a solution to the challenges of Continual Learning, where models must learn incrementally from a continuous data stream.
[src:streaming-algorithms/reservoir-sampling] The KLRS algorithm was designed to create a flexible policy that matches class percentages in the buffer to a target distribution while employing Reservoir Sampling techniques.
[src:streaming-algorithms/reservoir-sampling] This is achieved by minimizing the Kullback-Leibler (KL) divergence between the current buffer distribution and the desired target distribution.
[src:streaming-algorithms/reservoir-sampling] KLRS generalizes earlier methods like Reservoir Sampling and Class-Balancing Reservoir Sampling, as verified by experiments using confidence intervals, demonstrating its broader applicability and improved performance.
[src:streaming-algorithms/reservoir-sampling] The KLRS algorithm operates by maintaining a buffer of size and updating its contents as new data points arrive in a stream.
[src:streaming-algorithms/reservoir-sampling] Suppose one wanted to draw k random cards from a deck of cards.
[src:streaming-algorithms/reservoir-sampling] A natural approach would be to shuffle the deck and then take the top k cards.
[src:streaming-algorithms/reservoir-sampling] Note that although the rest of the cards are shuffled, only the first k are important in the present context.
[src:streaming-algorithms/reservoir-sampling] Therefore, the array R need only track the cards in the first k positions while performing the shuffle, reducing the amount of memory needed.
[src:streaming-algorithms/reservoir-sampling] Since the order of the first k cards is immaterial, the first loop can be removed and R can be initialized to be the first k items of the input.
[src:streaming-algorithms/reservoir-sampling] Reservoir sampling makes the assumption that the desired sample fits into main memory, often implying that k is a constant independent of n.
[src:streaming-algorithms/reservoir-sampling] In applications where we would like to select a large subset of the input list (say a third, i.e. $k=n/3$ ), other methods need to be adopted.
[src:streaming-algorithms/reservoir-sampling] Distributed implementations for this problem have been proposed.
[src:streaming-algorithms/streaming-algorithm] In computer science, **streaming algorithms** process input data streams as a sequence of items, typically making just one pass (or a few passes) through the data.
[src:streaming-algorithms/streaming-algorithm] These algorithms are designed to operate with limited memory, generally logarithmic in the size of the stream and/or in the maximum value in the stream, and may also have limited processing time per item.
[src:streaming-algorithms/streaming-algorithm] As a result of these constraints, streaming algorithms often produce approximate answers based on a summary or "sketch" of the data stream.
[src:streaming-algorithms/streaming-algorithm] Though streaming algorithms had already been studied by Munro and Paterson as early as 1978, as well as Philippe Flajolet and G.
[src:streaming-algorithms/streaming-algorithm] Nigel Martin in 1982/83, the field of streaming algorithms was first formalized and popularized in a 1996 paper by Noga Alon, Yossi Matias, and Mario Szegedy.
[src:streaming-algorithms/streaming-algorithm] Semi-streaming algorithms were introduced in 2005 as a relaxation of streaming algorithms for graphs, in which the space allowed is linear in the number of vertices *n*, but only logarithmic in the number of edges *m*.
[src:streaming-algorithms/streaming-algorithm] This relaxation is still meaningful for dense graphs, and can solve interesting problems (such as connectivity) that are insoluble in $o(n)$ space.
[src:streaming-algorithms/streaming-algorithm] In the data stream model, some or all of the input is represented as a finite sequence of integers (from some finite domain) which is generally not available for random access, but instead arrives one at a time in a "stream".
[src:streaming-algorithms/streaming-algorithm] If the stream has length *n* and the domain has size *m*, algorithms are generally constrained to use space that is logarithmic in *m* and *n*.
[src:streaming-algorithms/streaming-algorithm] They can generally make only some small constant number of passes over the stream, sometimes just one.
[src:streaming-algorithms/streaming-algorithm] Much of the streaming literature is concerned with computing statistics on frequency distributions that are too large to be stored.
[src:streaming-algorithms/streaming-algorithm] For this class of problems, there is a vector $\mathbf {a} =(a_{1},\dots ,a_{n})$ (initialized to the zero vector $\mathbf {0}$ ) that has updates presented to it in a stream.
[src:streaming-algorithms/streaming-algorithm] The goal of these algorithms is to compute functions of $\mathbf {a}$ using considerably less space than it would take to represent $\mathbf {a}$ precisely.
[src:streaming-algorithms/streaming-algorithm] There are two common models for updating such streams, called the "cash register" and "turnstile" models.
[src:streaming-algorithms/streaming-algorithm] In the cash register model, each update is of the form $\langle i,c\rangle$ , so that $a_{i}$ is incremented by some positive integer c .
[src:streaming-algorithms/streaming-algorithm] A notable special case is when $c=1$ (only unit insertions are permitted).
[src:streaming-algorithms/streaming-algorithm] In the turnstile model, each update is of the form $\langle i,c\rangle$ , so that $a_{i}$ is incremented by some (possibly negative) integer c .
[src:streaming-algorithms/streaming-algorithm] In the "strict turnstile" model, no $a_{i}$ at any time may be less than zero.
[src:streaming-algorithms/streaming-algorithm] Several papers also consider the "sliding window" model.
[src:streaming-algorithms/streaming-algorithm] In this model, the function of interest is computing over a fixed-size window in the stream.
[src:streaming-algorithms/streaming-algorithm] As the stream progresses, items from the end of the window are removed from consideration while new items from the stream take their place.
[src:streaming-algorithms/streaming-algorithm] Besides the above frequency-based problems, some other types of problems have also been studied.
[src:streaming-algorithms/streaming-algorithm] Many graph problems are solved in the setting where the adjacency matrix or the adjacency list of the graph is streamed in some unknown order.
[src:streaming-algorithms/streaming-algorithm] There are also some problems that are very dependent on the order of the stream (i.e., asymmetric functions), such as counting the number of inversions in a stream and finding the longest increasing subsequence.
[src:streaming-algorithms/streaming-algorithm] These algorithms have many similarities with online algorithms since they both require decisions to be made before all data are available, but they are not identical.
[src:streaming-algorithms/streaming-algorithm] Data stream algorithms only have limited memory available but they may be able to defer action until a group of points arrive, while online algorithms are required to take action as soon as each point arrives.
[src:streaming-algorithms/streaming-algorithm] If the algorithm is an approximation algorithm then the accuracy of the answer is another key factor.
[src:streaming-algorithms/streaming-algorithm] The accuracy is often stated as an $(\epsilon ,\delta )$ approximation meaning that the algorithm achieves an error of less than $\epsilon$ with probability $1-\delta$ .
[src:streaming-algorithms/streaming-algorithm] Streaming algorithms have several applications in networking such as monitoring network links for elephant flows, counting the number of distinct flows, estimating the distribution of flow sizes, and so on.
[src:streaming-algorithms/streaming-algorithm] They also have applications in databases, such as estimating the size of a join .
[src:streaming-algorithms/streaming-algorithm] The kth frequency moment of a set of frequencies $\mathbf {a}$ is defined as $F_{k}(\mathbf {a} )=\sum _{i=1}^{n}a_{i}^{k}$ .
[src:streaming-algorithms/streaming-algorithm] The first moment $F_{1}$ is simply the sum of the frequencies (i.e., the total count).
[src:streaming-algorithms/streaming-algorithm] The second moment $F_{2}$ is useful for computing statistical properties of the data, such as the Gini coefficient of variation. $F_{\infty }$ is defined as the frequency of the most frequent items.
[src:streaming-algorithms/streaming-algorithm] The seminal paper of Alon, Matias, and Szegedy dealt with the problem of estimating the frequency moments.
[src:streaming-algorithms/streaming-algorithm] A direct approach to find the frequency moments requires to maintain a register mi for all distinct elements *a**i* ∈ (1,2,3,4,...,*N*) which requires at least memory of order $\Omega (N)$ .
[src:streaming-algorithms/streaming-algorithm] But we have space limitations and require an algorithm that computes in much lower memory.
[src:streaming-algorithms/streaming-algorithm] This can be achieved by using approximations instead of exact values.
[src:streaming-algorithms/streaming-algorithm] An algorithm that computes an (*ε,δ*)approximation of Fk, where F'k is the (*ε,δ*)- approximated value of Fk.
[src:streaming-algorithms/streaming-algorithm] Where *ε* is the approximation parameter and *δ* is the confidence parameter.
[src:streaming-algorithms/streaming-algorithm] Flajolet et al. in introduced a probabilistic method of counting which was inspired from a paper by Robert Morris.
[src:streaming-algorithms/streaming-algorithm] Morris in his paper says that if the requirement of accuracy is dropped, a counter *n* can be replaced by a counter log *n* which can be stored in log log *n* bits.
[src:streaming-algorithms/streaming-algorithm] Flajolet et al. in improved this method by using a hash function h which is assumed to uniformly distribute the element in the hash space (a binary string of length L).
[src:streaming-algorithms/streaming-algorithm] Let $\rho (y)$ represents the position of least significant 1-bit in the binary representation of yi with a suitable convention for $\rho (0)$ .
[src:streaming-algorithms/streaming-algorithm] Let *A* be the sequence of data stream of length *M* whose cardinality need to be determined.
[src:streaming-algorithms/streaming-algorithm] hash space where the ρ(*hashedvalues*) are recorded.
[src:streaming-algorithms/streaming-algorithm] The below algorithm then determines approximate cardinality of *A*.
[src:streaming-algorithms/streaming-algorithm] If there are *N* distinct elements in a data stream.
[src:streaming-algorithms/streaming-algorithm] The previous algorithm describes the first attempt to approximate *F*0 in the data stream by Flajolet and Martin.
[src:streaming-algorithms/streaming-algorithm] Their algorithm picks a random hash function which they assume to uniformly distribute the hash values in hash space.
[src:streaming-algorithms/streaming-algorithm] Bar-Yossef et al. in introduced k-minimum value algorithm for determining number of distinct elements in data stream.
[src:streaming-algorithms/streaming-algorithm] They used a similar hash function *h* which can be normalized to [0,1] as $h:[m]\rightarrow [0,1]$ .
[src:streaming-algorithms/streaming-algorithm] But they fixed a limit *t* to number of values in hash space.
[src:streaming-algorithms/streaming-algorithm] The value of *t* is assumed of the order $O\left({\dfrac {1}{\varepsilon _{2}}}\right)$ (i.e. less approximation-value *ε* requires more *t*).
[src:streaming-algorithms/streaming-algorithm] KMV algorithm keeps only *t*-smallest hash values in the hash space.
[src:streaming-algorithms/streaming-algorithm] After all the *m* values of stream have arrived, $\upsilon =\mathrm {Max} (h(a_{i}))$ is used to calculate $F'_{0}={\dfrac {t}{\upsilon }}$ .
[src:streaming-algorithms/streaming-algorithm] That is, in a close-to uniform hash space, they expect at-least *t* elements to be less than $O\left({\dfrac {t}{F_{0}}}\right)$ .
[src:streaming-algorithms/streaming-algorithm] KMV algorithm can be implemented in $O\left(\left({\dfrac {1}{\varepsilon _{2}}}\right)\cdot \log(m)\right)$ memory bits space.
[src:streaming-algorithms/streaming-algorithm] Each hash value requires space of order $O(\log(m))$ memory bits.
[src:streaming-algorithms/streaming-algorithm] There are hash values of the order $O\left({\dfrac {1}{\varepsilon _{2}}}\right)$ .
[src:streaming-algorithms/streaming-algorithm] The access time can be reduced if we store the *t* hash values in a binary tree.
[src:streaming-algorithms/streaming-algorithm] Thus the time complexity will be reduced to $O\left(\log \left({\dfrac {1}{\varepsilon }}\right)\cdot \log(m)\right)$ .
[src:streaming-algorithms/streaming-algorithm] Alon et al. estimates Fk by defining random variables that can be computed within given space and time.
[src:streaming-algorithms/streaming-algorithm] The expected value of random variables gives the approximate value of Fk.
[src:streaming-algorithms/streaming-algorithm] Assume length of sequence *m* is known in advance.
[src:streaming-algorithms/streaming-algorithm] Algorithm takes *S*2 random variable $Y_{1},Y_{2},...,Y_{S2}$ and outputs the median Y .
[src:streaming-algorithms/streaming-algorithm] Where Yi is the average of Xij where 1 ≤ *j* ≤ *S*1.
[src:streaming-algorithms/streaming-algorithm] Now calculate expectation of random variable *E*(*X*).
[src:streaming-algorithms/streaming-algorithm] From the algorithm to calculate Fk discussed above, we can see that each random variable X stores value of ap and r.
[src:streaming-algorithms/streaming-algorithm] So, to compute X we need to maintain only log(*n*) bits for storing ap and log(*n*) bits for storing r.
[src:streaming-algorithms/streaming-algorithm] Total number of random variable X will be the ⁠ $S_{1}*S_{2}$ ⁠.
[src:streaming-algorithms/streaming-algorithm] The previous algorithm calculates $F_{2}$ in order of $O({\sqrt {n}}(\log m+\log n))$ memory bits.
[src:streaming-algorithms/streaming-algorithm] Alon et al. in simplified this algorithm using four-wise independent random variable with values mapped to $\{-1,1\}$ .
[src:streaming-algorithms/streaming-algorithm] In the data stream model, the **frequent elements problem** is to output a set of elements that constitute more than some fixed fraction of the stream.
[src:streaming-algorithms/streaming-algorithm] A special case is the **majority problem**, which is to determine whether or not any value constitutes a majority of the stream.
[src:streaming-algorithms/streaming-algorithm] More formally, fix some positive constant *c* > 1, let the length of the stream be *m*, and let *f**i* denote the frequency of value *i* in the stream.
[src:streaming-algorithms/streaming-algorithm] The frequent elements problem is to output the set { *i* | *f**i* > m/c }.
[src:streaming-algorithms/streaming-algorithm] Detecting events in data streams is often done using a heavy hitters algorithm as listed above: the most frequent items and their frequency are determined using one of these algorithms, then the largest increase over the previous time point is reported as trend.
[src:streaming-algorithms/streaming-algorithm] This approach can be refined by using exponentially weighted moving averages and variance for normalization.
[src:streaming-algorithms/streaming-algorithm] Counting the number of distinct elements in a stream (sometimes called the *F*0 moment) is another problem that has been well studied.
[src:streaming-algorithms/streaming-algorithm] The first algorithm for it was proposed by Flajolet and Martin.
[src:streaming-algorithms/streaming-algorithm] In 2010, Daniel Kane, Jelani Nelson and David Woodruff found an asymptotically optimal algorithm for this problem.
[src:streaming-algorithms/streaming-algorithm] It uses *O*(*ε*2 + log *d*) space, with *O*(1) worst-case update and reporting times, as well as universal hash functions and a r-wise independent hash family where *r* = Ω(log(1/*ε*) / log log(1/*ε*)).
[src:streaming-algorithms/streaming-algorithm] Learn a model (e.g. a classifier) by a single pass over a training set.
[src:streaming-algorithms/streaming-algorithm] Lower bounds have been computed for many of the data streaming problems that have been studied.
[src:streaming-algorithms/streaming-algorithm] By far, the most common technique for computing these lower bounds has been using communication complexity.
